01:34.367 --> 01:37.367
Pittsburgh is a city
of neighborhoods,

01:37.400 --> 01:41.300
each with its own
rites and rituals,

01:41.333 --> 01:46.800
a patchwork of cultures that
took shape over a century ago.

01:46.833 --> 01:49.900
Back then, the city was a
beacon of hope and possibility

01:49.933 --> 01:51.700
for people from
all over the world,

01:51.733 --> 01:57.533
offering the promise of work,
prosperity, a new life.

01:57.567 --> 01:59.833
Pittsburgh could have been
another company town

01:59.867 --> 02:03.467
gone to beautiful ruin,

02:03.500 --> 02:06.233
but something happened.

02:06.267 --> 02:08.133
The city started
to pop up on lists

02:08.167 --> 02:11.400
of the most livable
places in America.

02:11.433 --> 02:14.300
It became attractive to a new
wave of people from elsewhere

02:14.333 --> 02:18.633
looking to reinvent themselves
and make a new world.

02:18.667 --> 02:21.333
And so we find ourselves
asking the same questions

02:21.367 --> 02:23.567
we ask in other cities
in transition.

02:23.600 --> 02:26.967
Are the new arrivals,
new, money, new ideas,

02:27.000 --> 02:29.833
saving the city
or cannibalizing it?

02:29.867 --> 02:31.967
Who will live in the
Pittsburgh of the future,

02:32.000 --> 02:35.333
and will there be room for
the people who stayed true,

02:35.367 --> 02:38.367
stuck with it their whole lives?

02:45.400 --> 02:45.900
