I joined a group
of foodie all-stars

11:32.100 --> 11:35.833
about 20 miles outside
of town for a meal.

11:39.233 --> 11:42.700
Are there typical, iconic
Pittsburgher qualities?

11:42.733 --> 11:45.133
You probably worked here
and brag about working here.

11:45.167 --> 11:47.167
You complain about Millennials.

11:47.200 --> 11:49.533
You complain about the people
on the street harassing you.

11:49.567 --> 11:52.167
You don't like
anything new at all.

11:52.200 --> 11:54.900
- Right.
- You're describing me.

11:54.933 --> 11:57.000
The menu is flipping good.

11:57.033 --> 11:59.133
Right in my happy zone.

11:59.167 --> 12:01.000
Racks of pork rib,

12:01.033 --> 12:03.300
grilled hearts
of escarole and turnips,

12:03.333 --> 12:05.200
a sauce made from
the pork drippings,

12:05.233 --> 12:07.500
and four types of sausage.

12:07.533 --> 12:09.467
- What now?
- Look at this. Whoa.

12:09.500 --> 12:12.133
- The food's amazing.
- That's titanic.

12:12.167 --> 12:14.400
I don't want to speak about
Pittsburgh in a dismissive way,

12:14.433 --> 12:19.500
but it was not known
before being what it is today.

12:19.533 --> 12:22.667
People are talking a lot
about the food scene here.

12:22.700 --> 12:26.467
'Twas not always so.
What were people eating before?

12:26.500 --> 12:28.133
You know, steak and potatoes.

12:28.167 --> 12:30.167
You know,
living in San Francisco

12:30.200 --> 12:33.833
as a young person in your 20s,
you were going out to eat.

12:33.867 --> 12:35.467
That was really important,

12:35.500 --> 12:37.333
and we all knew
about the restaurants,

12:37.367 --> 12:39.160
whether you were in the
restaurant business or not.

12:39.167 --> 12:41.567
- Right.
- And that wasn't Pittsburgh.

12:41.600 --> 12:44.067
When I opened Dinette
in 2008, you know,

12:44.100 --> 12:46.333
I'm expecting people
like me to be coming in.

12:46.367 --> 12:49.233
I'm 29. That's who I'm
building this restaurant for,

12:49.267 --> 12:51.967
and everyone was...
56.

12:52.000 --> 12:54.000
Yeah, my parents' age or older.

13:03.033 --> 13:05.133
You know, I thought to myself,

13:05.167 --> 13:06.333
I'm going to this neighborhood

13:06.367 --> 13:08.233
that's basically desolate.

13:08.267 --> 13:10.300
I'm gonna take this
building that's been...

13:10.333 --> 13:12.467
It's a restaurant that's been
closed for seven years,

13:12.500 --> 13:15.067
and, you know, I'm gonna
do something nice here.

13:15.100 --> 13:16.660
You know, I didn't
expect the reaction I got

13:16.667 --> 13:18.367
from the actual people
that lived around me.

13:18.400 --> 13:19.800
Right.

13:19.833 --> 13:21.467
You know,
which was not positive.

13:21.500 --> 13:23.300
They liked it the way
it was, you know?

13:23.333 --> 13:24.693
That was their life,
and then, you know,

13:24.700 --> 13:26.367
I move in and all of a sudden,

13:26.400 --> 13:28.833
I open this restaurant and
people with nice, fancy cars

13:28.867 --> 13:30.833
are taking their parking spaces,

13:30.867 --> 13:32.333
and now I'm a yuppie gentrifier.

13:32.367 --> 13:33.700
- Well.
- You know what I mean?

13:33.733 --> 13:35.133
You know, own it.

13:35.167 --> 13:37.133
Sometimes it
kind of hurts, right,

13:37.167 --> 13:39.500
as a restaurant owner
or small business owner

13:39.533 --> 13:41.900
because there are always haters
out there, and you feel like,

13:41.933 --> 13:44.500
okay, so somebody wants me
to be a small business owner,

13:44.533 --> 13:47.400
and take care of my employees,
and then also on me,

13:47.433 --> 13:49.467
they're gonna talk
about gentrification, right?

13:49.500 --> 13:51.867
Like, you're just trying
to do your thing.

13:51.900 --> 13:54.300
You're just trying
to do something good.

13:54.333 --> 13:55.667
Right.

13:55.700 --> 13:57.660
And you're trying to do it
for you, and you should.

13:57.667 --> 14:00.200
Yeah, but I don't know.
I mean, for me it's different.

14:00.233 --> 14:02.167
Like, I definitely was thinking

14:02.200 --> 14:04.067
about the neighborhood
when I did it.

14:04.100 --> 14:06.567
Like, I'm not some egomaniac
who thinks that, like,

14:06.600 --> 14:10.400
just putting out
my food is a reason, like,

14:10.433 --> 14:13.167
so everyone can enjoy
the, like, artistry of my food.

14:13.200 --> 14:14.833
That's why I'm opening
a restaurant.

14:14.867 --> 14:16.567
That's not the point.
Well, I mean,

14:16.600 --> 14:19.633
not to disagree with anything
that you just said,

14:19.667 --> 14:22.333
but, like, I didn't open
Cure in Lawrenceville

14:22.367 --> 14:24.800
because I wanted to change
the neighborhood.

14:24.833 --> 14:28.467
I honestly opened Cure
for me 100%.

14:28.500 --> 14:29.967
I was, like,
struggling professionally,

14:30.000 --> 14:31.533
struggling personally.

14:31.567 --> 14:35.133
Cure was all about
satisfying me, like, 100%.

14:35.167 --> 14:39.500
If I'm running a high-end
restaurant in Pittsburgh.

14:39.533 --> 14:42.900
Who am I employing
as porters, dishwashers?

