30:55.267 --> 30:57.967
This is where my dad
worked for 46 years.

30:58.000 --> 31:00.867
The last time I was there
it looked like a spaceship,

31:00.900 --> 31:02.633
it was all so modernized.

31:02.667 --> 31:05.700
There's probably 500 people
doing the work of, you know,

31:05.733 --> 31:09.233
when my dad was there, 5,000.

31:09.267 --> 31:11.000
So what do you think
it's gonna take?

31:11.033 --> 31:13.467
Or do you think
it's just gonna die?

31:13.500 --> 31:15.467
I think we're in the last
stages of capitalism,

31:15.500 --> 31:17.160
because this is...
You're talking socialism?

31:17.167 --> 31:18.900
Yeah, yeah, I'm talking
socialism, yeah.

31:18.933 --> 31:21.400
When the magical workers'
paradise arrives,

31:21.433 --> 31:23.500
will Braddock be here?
Will Braddock be here?

31:23.533 --> 31:26.233
I wish there was, like,
a simple answer to all this.

31:28.667 --> 31:30.733
I'll die before I actually
see what happens.

31:30.767 --> 31:33.567
I'm not gonna know the story,
and it really bothers me.

31:33.600 --> 31:36.033
It's the only thing I hate
about the thought of dying

31:36.067 --> 31:38.367
is that I don't know
what the story's gonna be.

31:50.267 --> 31:53.567
Braddock, Pennsylvania,
sustained a real traumatic

31:53.600 --> 31:55.667
unraveling that was common

31:55.700 --> 31:58.367
in Rust Belt
communities and towns,

31:58.400 --> 32:01.567
but ours was a particularly
severe example of that.

32:01.600 --> 32:04.067
- Average income?
- We're around $20,000, so...

32:04.100 --> 32:06.900
- Which is...
- Which is substantially below

32:06.933 --> 32:08.833
the Pennsylvania average.

32:08.867 --> 32:10.826
Yeah, I'll have mothers
that will call me on a Monday,

32:10.833 --> 32:12.467
and, you know, by Friday

32:12.500 --> 32:14.393
they're gonna be out of food
to feed their three kids,

32:14.400 --> 32:16.367
and this happens
quite regularly.

32:16.400 --> 32:19.400
John Fetterman does not look
like your typical mayor,

32:19.433 --> 32:20.967
and he isn't.

32:21.000 --> 32:22.633
He came to Braddock in 2001

32:22.667 --> 32:24.967
to help at-risk youth
get their GEDs,

32:25.000 --> 32:27.800
and ran for office here in one
of the most depressed towns

32:27.833 --> 32:29.833
in the state four years later.

32:29.867 --> 32:33.567
His wife, Gisele, is from Rio,
and she runs a nonprofit

32:33.600 --> 32:36.367
that provides food and
essential supplies for more

32:36.400 --> 32:38.633
than 1,500 families each month.

32:38.667 --> 32:42.167
A lot of people
in this country are angry.

32:42.200 --> 32:44.467
They feel that their
anger has not been

32:44.500 --> 32:45.967
acknowledged in any way,

32:46.000 --> 32:47.308
and frankly,
I think they're right.

32:47.333 --> 32:49.800
- Yep.
- There is a sense,

32:49.833 --> 32:52.467
particularly in rural,
white America,

32:52.500 --> 32:55.800
of aggrievement
that nobody's listening,

32:55.833 --> 32:57.633
nobody's caring about them.

32:57.667 --> 33:00.033
I mean, Western PA
played a pivotal role

33:00.067 --> 33:01.833
in helping elect Donald Trump,

33:01.867 --> 33:03.367
and he turned Pennsylvania red

33:03.400 --> 33:05.300
for the first time since '88,

33:05.333 --> 33:07.467
and did it so with a margin
of about 44,000 people,

33:07.500 --> 33:09.567
a lot of whom,
as you referenced,

33:09.600 --> 33:11.300
are disaffected Democrats.

33:11.333 --> 33:13.300
Somebody phrased it to me
where it's like,

33:13.333 --> 33:15.133
"If the economy's
not gonna work for me,

33:15.167 --> 33:17.167
then I don't want it
to work for anybody."

33:17.200 --> 33:20.833
How does that manifest itself
on a local basis for you?

33:20.867 --> 33:22.333
It's an honor to be involved,

33:22.367 --> 33:25.633
and I hope whoever it is
that's next

33:25.667 --> 33:27.633
realizes that you need

33:27.667 --> 33:30.367
to go outside your community's
borders to bring help in,

33:30.400 --> 33:32.367
and that's what
I've tried to do.

33:32.400 --> 33:34.733
That means people like
four-time Super Bowl champion,

33:34.767 --> 33:36.333
Franco Harris,

33:36.367 --> 33:38.167
and if you're wondering
how he could help,

33:38.200 --> 33:41.133
you might be surprised
by the answer.

33:41.167 --> 33:44.167
Franco and I hope to be
growing medical marijuana

33:44.200 --> 33:46.300
about a block from here.
We put in an application

33:46.333 --> 33:50.167
for a large grow facility
here in our community,

33:50.200 --> 33:52.533
which would be a real
economic shot in the arm,

33:52.567 --> 33:53.967
and it's been a real honor

33:54.000 --> 33:56.167
to partner with someone
like Franco.

33:56.200 --> 33:58.133
Why is this a cause for you?

33:58.167 --> 34:00.133
I'm a believer
in medical marijuana

34:00.167 --> 34:02.000
because of pain management,

34:02.033 --> 34:06.067
and I run into many ex-players

34:06.100 --> 34:07.800
who deal with pain management,

34:07.833 --> 34:10.967
and, right now, the
alternatives don't look good,

34:11.000 --> 34:12.500
and we have a lot of problems

34:12.533 --> 34:13.926
with the alternatives
that they've had so.

34:13.933 --> 34:15.632
There's no doubt about that.

34:15.667 --> 34:18.233
Western PA's been ravaged
by the opioid crisis,

34:18.266 --> 34:22.800
and it positions us
for the eventual legalization

34:22.833 --> 34:24.833
of marijuana and...

34:24.867 --> 34:26.900
It would also pull
Braddock out of Act 47,

34:26.933 --> 34:29.533
so we would no longer
be fiscally bankrupt.

34:32.433 --> 34:34.033
Braddock lost its initial bid

34:34.067 --> 34:35.900
for a medical marijuana license,

34:35.933 --> 34:37.467
but there are a few other

34:37.500 --> 34:39.333
madcap entrepreneurial
efforts in town,

34:39.367 --> 34:42.199
lone dreamers with a plan.

34:42.233 --> 34:45.800
One such dreamer
is chef Kevin Sousa.

34:45.833 --> 34:48.467
Kevin was the first
of a new generation of chefs

34:48.500 --> 34:50.533
to bring national
attention to Pittsburgh

34:50.567 --> 34:52.132
when he opened his restaurant,

34:52.167 --> 34:55.333
Salt of the Earth, in 2010.

34:55.367 --> 34:57.033
What are we looking at
here, Chef?

34:57.067 --> 34:59.033
- All right, so...
- Beautiful.

34:59.067 --> 35:02.700
We are landlocked,
so seafood is tough.

35:02.733 --> 35:05.967
This is Lake Erie Walleye Pike,

35:06.000 --> 35:09.067
some new potatoes from the farm,

35:09.100 --> 35:10.733
some of the crackling
from the fish,

35:10.767 --> 35:14.167
took the skin crisped it up,
it's nice and crunchy,

35:14.200 --> 35:16.633
and then just a lot
of little farm herbs.

35:16.667 --> 35:18.367
Now, after some bumps
in the road,

35:18.400 --> 35:20.467
he's improbably turning
this building,

35:20.500 --> 35:23.467
a former Chevy dealership,
into his latest restaurant,

35:23.500 --> 35:25.367
Superior Motors.

35:25.400 --> 35:27.800
Opening night is less
than a month away.

35:27.833 --> 35:29.400
Do I have to eat this?

35:29.433 --> 35:31.967
I mean, it's too pretty.
It's too pretty to eat. Jeez.

35:32.000 --> 35:33.093
The fish is amazing, by the way.

35:33.100 --> 35:34.467
Oh, thank you very much.

35:34.500 --> 35:35.693
Where were you born and raised?

35:35.700 --> 35:37.233
McKees Rocks.

35:37.267 --> 35:38.883
- You're close to your roots.
- Yeah, yeah,

35:38.900 --> 35:42.067
in locality and in spirit.

35:42.100 --> 35:44.133
Is the restaurant
business any... I mean,

35:44.167 --> 35:45.826
'cause I know, you know,
it's been bumpy for you.

35:45.833 --> 35:47.167
It has.

35:47.200 --> 35:48.700
You over-expanded
or over-extended?

35:48.733 --> 35:50.333
Over-expanded with no capital.

35:50.367 --> 35:52.333
I just thought we were
gonna open the doors

35:52.367 --> 35:54.200
and everyone was gonna
go apeshit

35:54.233 --> 35:57.300
for whatever it is
that I served, and I learned.

35:57.333 --> 35:59.967
As serendipity would have it,
I met John.

36:00.000 --> 36:03.233
Asked if I'd be interested in
going for a walk in Braddock.

36:03.267 --> 36:06.200
Came out to Braddock.
Fell in love.

36:06.233 --> 36:07.800
- With Braddock, not me.
- With Braddock.

36:09.867 --> 36:12.300
You know, it reminded me of
McKees Rocks, and McKees Rocks,

36:12.333 --> 36:15.967
you know, has suffered much in
the same way as Braddock has.

36:16.000 --> 36:18.500
Kevin says he has ambitions

36:18.533 --> 36:20.667
that go beyond turning a profit.

36:20.700 --> 36:23.500
His restaurant hopes to
provide tuition-free training,

36:23.533 --> 36:25.733
and they're partnering
with a local urban farm

36:25.767 --> 36:28.200
that employs high school
students to grow produce

36:28.233 --> 36:30.567
in the shadows
of the old steel mill.

36:30.600 --> 36:33.533
And though we are talking
a swank, high-end restaurant

36:33.567 --> 36:36.300
designed to attract the monied
classes from out of town,

36:36.333 --> 36:40.467
locals will be offered
steeply discounted meals.

36:40.500 --> 36:44.000
So this is beautiful,
grass-fed beef short ribs

36:44.033 --> 36:48.467
sitting on a bed of lightly
blanched milkweed buds.

36:48.500 --> 36:52.700
On top, a bunch of
over-wintered sun choke chips.

36:52.733 --> 36:54.233
- Nice.
- Awesome.

36:54.267 --> 36:56.500
That's the compliment
I was looking for.

36:56.533 --> 37:00.067
I was trying to work
that one out.

37:00.100 --> 37:02.467
So what happens
if everything works out

37:02.500 --> 37:04.233
the way you want it to,

37:04.267 --> 37:08.367
meaning people are driving
from all over the state,

37:08.400 --> 37:12.467
they're flying in to Pittsburgh
from all over the country,

37:12.500 --> 37:14.200
the parking lot is full,

37:14.233 --> 37:17.967
the place is packed
and fully booked every night?

37:18.000 --> 37:19.567
Then what happens?

37:19.600 --> 37:24.467
You're moving towards
the "G" word, and...

37:24.500 --> 37:26.033
No, not yet.

37:26.067 --> 37:29.133
Braddock is gentrification
proof, essentially.

37:29.167 --> 37:33.567
Our biggest challenge
has been abandonment,

37:33.600 --> 37:35.700
not people being displaced.

37:35.733 --> 37:38.167
To directly answer
your question, Chef,

37:38.200 --> 37:41.500
long after I've shuffled
off this mortal coil,

37:41.533 --> 37:44.167
the work will never
be done here.

37:44.200 --> 37:48.067
This is a decades' long process.

37:59.867 --> 38:03.567
♪

38:03.600 --> 38:06.233
If you head east 30 miles
from Pittsburgh,

38:06.267 --> 38:09.733
you'll find yourself
here in New Alexandria.

38:09.767 --> 38:11.733
It's a whole other world.

38:11.767 --> 38:15.133
No tech incubators here,
or fears of gentrification.

38:15.167 --> 38:18.967
Just good, heartland fun
on a Friday night.

38:19.000 --> 38:21.967
Family, fried dough
and demolition.

38:24.167 --> 38:26.733
Brooke Davis grew up
a few towns over from here.

38:26.767 --> 38:29.300
Tonight, she's driving
in the modified class,

38:29.333 --> 38:32.333
which means these cars
ain't exactly street legal.

38:32.367 --> 38:34.500
The winner gets 900 bucks.

38:34.533 --> 38:36.133
So how long you been doing this?

38:36.167 --> 38:38.967
Like getting into it?
Like, six years.

38:39.000 --> 38:41.067
And how did it all begin?

38:41.100 --> 38:43.833
Well, my dad, him and my uncle,

38:43.867 --> 38:46.733
you know, ran back in like,
the '80s and '90s,

38:46.767 --> 38:50.300
and it's just been something
I grew up with, so...

38:50.333 --> 38:52.633
I mean, the only other thing
we really do for fun

38:52.667 --> 38:57.567
is, you know, four-wheelers,
RZR Side by Sides, and hunt.

38:57.600 --> 38:59.967
Chris Quenzler's a welder
and considered

39:00.000 --> 39:02.467
one of the best demo mechanics
in the area.

39:02.500 --> 39:04.467
What are the rules as far
as the vehicle itself?

39:04.500 --> 39:06.833
I mean, can you build...
Theoretically you're allowed

39:06.867 --> 39:09.800
to build some monster
road warrior, you know, thing

39:09.833 --> 39:12.200
with some guitar dude
on the front and, you know,

39:12.233 --> 39:14.400
special hidden reinforcement
and spikes and shit?

39:14.433 --> 39:17.067
No, it's not "Death Race."
It's not "Death Race."

39:17.100 --> 39:18.833
Brooke is one
of the best girl drivers,

39:18.867 --> 39:20.467
female drivers, that I've seen.

39:20.500 --> 39:22.833
Wait a minute, what's
the difference between male

39:22.867 --> 39:24.200
and female drivers?
Is there any?

39:24.233 --> 39:25.900
There's not very many females

39:25.933 --> 39:27.333
that actually compete
with the guys.

39:27.367 --> 39:29.033
Yeah, but wouldn't it be great

39:29.067 --> 39:31.167
to see some big meathead
falling to his knees

39:31.200 --> 39:33.300
sobbing after you've
just totally destroyed...

39:33.333 --> 39:35.367
Maybe.
Depends on who they are.

39:35.400 --> 39:37.400
Some guy's been
talking shit all week.

39:37.433 --> 39:39.226
- Okay, yeah, yeah, definitely.
- I mean, come on.

39:39.233 --> 39:41.300
- Yeah.
- That would have to be good.

39:41.333 --> 39:42.860
So tonight, are you
gonna be the only girl...

39:42.867 --> 39:44.200
Probably I'm the only girl

39:44.233 --> 39:45.900
that's running out there
with the guys.

39:45.933 --> 39:47.226
Let us hope that tonight
is your night.

39:47.233 --> 39:48.700
I'm gonna get another shot.

39:48.733 --> 39:50.967
- Cheers.
- Yes. Cheers. Thank you.

39:59.533 --> 40:02.733
Countdown.
Ten, nine, eight,

40:02.767 --> 40:04.800
seven, six, five,

40:04.833 --> 40:06.400
four, three, two, one.

40:07.833 --> 40:08.333
♪

40:15.933 --> 40:18.467
Ooh!

40:18.500 --> 40:21.467
- The point of the game is?
- To be the last car running.

40:21.500 --> 40:23.900
Right.
Now what's the sweet spot?

40:23.933 --> 40:25.467
Where do you want to hit a car?

40:25.500 --> 40:28.467
- Wheels and tires.
- Wheels and tires.

40:28.500 --> 40:30.133
Yes.

40:30.167 --> 40:32.733
I like to look
for the weakest car,

40:32.767 --> 40:34.867
and get them out
of the way first.

40:41.167 --> 40:42.660
I'm running with guys
that have been running

40:42.667 --> 40:45.333
a really long time,

40:45.367 --> 40:48.300
and sometimes they think
I'm an easy target.

40:48.333 --> 40:51.700
Maybe I might get scared,
but definitely not like that.

40:51.733 --> 40:55.533
I can battle it out to the end.
I'm not gonna quit.

40:55.567 --> 40:57.567
♪

40:57.600 --> 40:59.467
What's the best part
of the driving?

40:59.500 --> 41:01.400
I mean, other than
winning, obviously.

41:01.433 --> 41:03.867
- I was gonna say winning.
- My best moment of driving

41:03.900 --> 41:05.167
is any time it comes down to me

41:05.200 --> 41:07.133
and my brother or one of...

41:07.167 --> 41:09.300
Me and my friends,
when you get down to the end,

41:09.333 --> 41:11.367
you know, and you beat
everybody else...

41:11.400 --> 41:13.400
So when you destroy
a friend's hopes and dreams,

41:13.433 --> 41:15.467
that's...
Oh, that's the best.

41:16.867 --> 41:17.367
♪

41:23.767 --> 41:24.967
Oh!

41:28.000 --> 41:28.500
♪

41:34.567 --> 41:38.733
By the end, most cars
are worse for wear.

41:38.767 --> 41:40.633
Brooke comes in third place,

41:40.667 --> 41:42.967
so she doesn't walk away
empty-handed.

41:43.000 --> 41:45.333
So I present her
with a $50 bill.

41:45.367 --> 41:48.400
You started off that good.
Congrats.

41:48.433 --> 41:51.133
Thank you.

41:51.167 --> 41:53.333
All over Western Pennsylvania,

41:53.367 --> 41:56.467
from small towns like this to
the largest city, Pittsburgh,

41:56.500 --> 41:59.467
people face the same
struggles as beleaguered,

41:59.500 --> 42:02.200
deindustrialized areas
across the country.

42:02.233 --> 42:04.133
How do you move into the future

42:04.167 --> 42:07.367
and hold on to what
you love about the past?

42:11.000 --> 42:13.800
There are probably
no easy answers.

42:13.833 --> 42:15.567
Things will change.

42:15.600 --> 42:17.233
They are changing,

42:17.267 --> 42:20.400
but for now,
let's just wreck some cars.

42:23.433 --> 42:26.867
♪

